Full Adversarial IEEE Review: "The EC2 Sweet Spot"

PRELIMINARY ASSESSMENT
I have read this paper in its entirety, cross-checked every numerical claim against the tables, traced every label/reference pair, and evaluated every methodological decision. What follows is an exhaustive adversarial review. I have found problems across all eight review dimensions. I will be direct and unsparing.

SECTION 1: NUMERICAL CONSISTENCY

Issue 1.1
Location: Abstract, paragraph 1 vs. Table 3 (tab:scaling_all_families), T-Family Phase 3.2
Type: Numerical
Severity: Critical
Description: The abstract states the t3.micro cluster achieves "1.28× speedup… relative to single-node deployments of the largest evaluated x86 instances (m5.4xlarge)." However, Table 3 (General Purpose M-Family block) shows the speedup of the m5.large horizontal cluster over the m5.4xlarge vertical as 1.28×. The 1.28× figure correctly belongs to the M-family cross-size comparison (1.22 min vs 1.56 min). The abstract implies this speedup is achieved by t3.micro instances against the m5.4xlarge, which is technically true in wall-clock time (both clusters achieve 1.22 min), but the framing collapses two distinct comparisons into one claim without disambiguation. More seriously, the abstract sentence structure attributes "1.28× speedup AND 89.4% cost reduction" to the same configuration. But 89.4% cost reduction is the cross-family comparison (t3.micro cluster $0.00211 vs m5.4xlarge $0.01997), while 1.28× is an intra-family comparison (m5.large cluster vs m5.4xlarge vertical). These are two different experimental comparisons being presented as if they were one result from a single experiment. This is misleading.
Suggested fix: Separate these two claims clearly. State: "A distributed cluster of 10× t3.micro instances achieves an 89.4% compute cost reduction relative to the m5.4xlarge; an intra-family cluster of 10× m5.large instances achieves a 1.28× wall-clock speedup over the same m5.4xlarge vertical baseline."

Issue 1.2
Location: Abstract vs. Introduction paragraph 4 vs. Section IV.C (Phase 3 Results)
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The abstract states "up to 93.3% of total execution time in unoptimized deployments." The introduction repeats this as "57.3%--93.3% of total processing time across T-family configurations." Table 3 confirms these values for Phase 3.1 T-family: Serial=57.3%, Parallel=93.3%, Vertical=74.0%. This is numerically consistent. However, the conclusion states "up to 93.3% of total processing time in unoptimized configurations" without the lower bound, and then later states "quantified this bottleneck at up to 93.3%." In Section IV.C.i, Phase 3.1 results are described as "setup activities consumed between 57.3% and 93.3% of total processing time across configurations." These are consistent with each other, but Section IV.D (Architecture, Codec, and Regional Impact) mentions M-family Phase 3.1 parallel overhead as 92.8% and C-family as 93.2% (Table 3). The claim that 93.3% is the maximum is therefore false — 93.3% is the T-family parallel value, while C-family shows 93.2% and M-family shows 92.8%. But wait: the T-family serial Phase 3.1 shows 57.3%, which is actually the minimum. So the range "57.3%--93.3%" is correct as stated. This is fine, but the framing in the abstract and conclusion ("up to 93.3%") is slightly misleading because it applies only to T-family parallel, and M and C families are actually lower. This should be stated more precisely.
Suggested fix: Qualify: "up to 93.3% (T-family parallel, Phase 3.1)" rather than presenting it as a universal maximum.

Issue 1.3
Location: Section IV.C.ii (Analysis and Validation) vs. Table 3
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The text states: "the M-family horizontal cluster achieved a 1.28× speedup (1.22 min vs. 1.56 min) over the vertical m5.4xlarge." Verification: 1.56/1.22 = 1.279..., rounds to 1.28×. Correct. "The C-family cluster achieved the fastest overall time of 1.18 minutes (1.26× speedup vs. 1.49 min)." Verification: 1.49/1.18 = 1.263..., rounds to 1.26×. Correct. "The T-family horizontal cluster (1.22 min) demonstrated the strongest relative speedup at 1.48× over the vertical t3.2xlarge (1.80 min)." Verification: 1.80/1.22 = 1.475..., rounds to 1.48×. Correct. Now checking Table 3: T-family Phase 3.2 Speedup vs Serial for Parallel = 2.23×. Verification: 2.72/1.22 = 2.229. Correct. For Vertical: 2.72/1.80 = 1.511, but Table 3 shows 1.51×. Correct. However, the abstract notes in the LaTeX source comment state: "1.28x speedup over m5.4xlarge: 10x m5.large cluster (1.22 min) vs m5.4xlarge vertical (1.56 min) = 1.56/1.22." This confirms the check. All these are consistent. However, there is an inconsistency in the abstract comment for "87.5% cost reduction": "(0.01689-0.00211)/0.01689 = 0.875." Verification: (0.01689-0.00211)/0.01689 = 0.01478/0.01689 = 0.8752. Correct. But the body text in Section IV.C.ii states "87.5% cost reduction relative to the c5.4xlarge ($0.01689)" — this uses t3.micro cluster cost ($0.00211) against c5.4xlarge vertical cost ($0.01689). This is a cross-family comparison (t3 vs c5) and is technically valid but should be clearly labeled as cross-family, not as a within-C-family result.
Suggested fix: Add explicit "cross-family" qualifier to both 89.4% and 87.5% cost reduction claims throughout.

Issue 1.4
Location: Section IV.C.ii vs. Table 3, M-family cost comparison
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The text states "The M-family cluster reduced cost by 2.3% ($0.01952 vs. $0.01997)." Verification: (0.01997-0.01952)/0.01997 = 0.00045/0.01997 = 0.02253 = 2.25%, which rounds to 2.3%. This is within rounding. But note: the "Cost Factor (vs Serial)" for M-family Phase 3.2 Parallel = 4.5×, and for Vertical = 4.6×. These are relative to the serial m5.large ($0.00434). 0.01952/0.00434 = 4.498 ≈ 4.5×. 0.01997/0.00434 = 4.602 ≈ 4.6×. Consistent. However, the phrase "cost reduction" for a 2.3% difference in the M-family horizontal vs vertical comparison is clinically negligible and the authors present it alongside the 89.4% cross-family reduction without adequate qualification. This is not a numerical error per se, but represents a rhetorical sleight of hand where a trivial within-family result is presented parallel to a dramatic cross-family result, potentially misleading readers about the actual economic advantages of horizontal scaling within the same family tier.
Suggested fix: Explicitly note that within-family cost savings are marginal (2.3% for M, 1.0% for C) and that the dominant economic argument for horizontal scaling rests on cross-family deployment (t3.micro vs m5/c5 verticals).

Issue 1.5
Location: Section IV.C.ii, last paragraph vs. Table 3
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The text claims "78.9% cost reduction (T-family, within-family comparison)." But Table 3 shows T-family Phase 3.2: Parallel cost = $0.00211, Vertical cost = $0.00998. (0.00998-0.00211)/0.00998 = 0.00787/0.00998 = 0.7886 ≈ 78.9%. This checks out. However, this 78.9% is comparing the t3.micro parallel cluster against the t3.2xlarge vertical — these are different instance types within the T-family, not the same instance type at different scales. Calling this "within-family" is misleading; it's actually a cross-size, cross-tier comparison. The "within-family" qualifier is misleading. Furthermore, this claim appears in the statistical validation subsection (IV.C.iii), which is an inappropriate location for an economic claim — this subsection should contain only statistical validation of speedup, not economic arguments. The structural placement compounds the semantic confusion.
Suggested fix: Relocate economic claims to the analysis subsection (IV.C.ii) and qualify as "cross-size within T-family."

Issue 1.6
Location: Table 2 (tab:final_comparison_consistent), t3.micro efficiency score vs. Introduction
Type: Numerical
Severity: Minor
Description: The introduction states "the t3.micro yields the highest cost-efficiency score" and references "136,424 vs. 4,662" (t3.micro vs c5.4xlarge). From Table 2: t3.micro 5-thread H.264 efficiency = 136,424. c5.4xlarge 10-thread H.264 efficiency = 4,662. Verification using Equation 1: Efficiency = 1/((cost/3600)×time). For t3.micro: 1/((0.0104/3600)×2.5373) = 1/(0.000002889×2.5373) = 1/0.000007330 = 136,424. For c5.4xlarge: 1/((0.6800/3600)×1.1355) = 1/(0.0001889×1.1355) = 1/0.0002145 = 4,663. The body says 4,662 but the arithmetic gives 4,663. This is a rounding discrepancy of 1 unit in a number with 4 significant figures, which is acceptable, but the paper should use consistent rounding rules.
Suggested fix: Use consistent rounding throughout efficiency calculations.

Issue 1.7
Location: Section IV.D (Regional Cost Disparities) vs. Table 4 (tab:regional_cost)
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The text states "an approximate 44% premium over us-east-1 (N. Virginia) across all utilized instance types." From Table 4: t3.micro: (0.0149-0.0104)/0.0104 = 43.3%. c5.large: (0.1220-0.0850)/0.0850 = 43.5%. m5.large: (0.1380-0.0960)/0.0960 = 43.75%. These average to ~43.5%, not 44%. The 44% claim is a minor overstatement. More importantly, the text also states "approximately 23-second performance inflation for m5.large horizontal in São Paulo." From Table 4: m5.large median in us-east-1 = 56.41s, in sa-east-1 = 79.85s. Difference = 23.44s. This is approximately 23 seconds. Correct. However, the absolute values diverge: m5.large in us-east-1 at 56.41s is inconsistent with Table 3 Phase 3.2 which shows m5.large horizontal effective encoding time of 0.26 min = 15.6 seconds (for a segment), and total parallel time of 1.22 min = 73.2 seconds. The 56.41s in Table 4 appears to represent a different metric than the total time in Table 3 — Table 4 appears to show median encoding time per segment (the effective encoding time metric), not total pipeline time. This is never explicitly stated and the column header "Median (s)" is ambiguous. If Table 4 represents per-segment encoding time, then the comparison between Table 3 (total pipeline time) and Table 4 (per-segment time) is inconsistent and could confuse readers.
Suggested fix: Add a clear footnote to Table 4 specifying that "Median (s)" refers to per-chunk encoding time within the horizontal cluster, not total pipeline completion time. Reconcile with Table 3 values explicitly.

Issue 1.8
Location: Phase 4, Network Egress section, cost calculation
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The text states: "delivering the 150 MB encoded payload incurs ≈$0.0135 in us-east-1." Verification: 150 MB = 0.146 GB. At $0.09/GB: 0.146 × 0.09 = $0.01318 ≈ $0.0132, not $0.0135. The authors likely used 0.150 GB directly: 0.150 × 0.09 = $0.0135, treating MB and GB with inconsistent conversion. 150 MB ≠ 0.150 GB; 150 MB = 150/1024 GB = 0.1465 GB. The $0.0135 figure uses a sloppy MB→GB conversion (treating 1 MB = 0.001 GB, i.e., SI decimal, when AWS typically uses binary prefixes). For a paper making precise economic claims, this is an unacceptable numerical error.
Suggested fix: Use 150 MiB = 0.1465 GiB or 150 MB = 0.1431 GiB and recalculate: 0.1431 × 0.09 = $0.0129. Update the claim accordingly and clarify whether MB or MiB is intended.

Issue 1.9
Location: Table 3, M-family Phase 3.2 cost values vs. text claim of 89.4% reduction
Type: Numerical
Severity: Minor
Description: The 89.4% claim uses t3.micro cluster cost $0.00211 vs m5.4xlarge vertical $0.01997. But the t3.micro is from the T-family section of Table 3, while m5.4xlarge is from the M-family section. These two numbers come from different experimental sub-studies (different instance families, different cost-per-hour bases). The comparison is arithmetically valid but ecologically questionable — the t3.micro cluster uses 10 instances at $0.0104/h each, while the m5.4xlarge costs $0.768/h. The paper never discusses whether these represent equivalent service-level guarantees (burstable vs. sustained performance). For a rigorous IEEE paper, this cross-family comparison requires explicit justification of comparability.
Suggested fix: Add a paragraph discussing the service-level equivalence assumptions underlying cross-family comparisons, particularly the implications of burstable vs. sustained compute for production SLA guarantees.

Issue 1.10
Location: Table 5 (tab:chunk_sensitivity), T-family 120s chunk
Type: Numerical
Severity: Major
Description: The table shows 5× t3.micro at 120s chunks yields "2.04 min" with "0.88× speedup" vs vertical (t3.2xlarge at 1.80 min Phase 3.2). Verification: 1.80/2.04 = 0.882×. This is listed as slower than vertical (correctly noted with asterisk). But the text claims "120-second chunks with only 5 nodes reduce provisioning calls but fail to exploit parallelism sufficiently, as the higher per-instance encoding burden dominates." This explanation is logically inconsistent: if provisioning overhead is the dominant factor (as the paper argues throughout), then 5 nodes should have less provisioning overhead than 10 nodes. The slowdown for 5 nodes with 120s chunks should be explained by insufficient parallelism, not "higher per-instance encoding burden." Each node encodes a 2-minute segment instead of 1-minute, effectively doubling encoding time per node to ~0.44 min. Plus provisioning ~1.0 min. Total ≈ 1.44 min, yet observed is 2.04 min. The discrepancy of 0.60 min is not explained. The authors need to account for this gap.
Suggested fix: Provide a breakdown of where the 2.04 min goes for the 5-node 120s chunk configuration. The claim that encoding burden "dominates" is not supported by the arithmetic.

SECTION 2: TECHNICAL CORRECTNESS

Issue 2.1
Location: Section III (Methodology), Phase 2 statistical analysis paragraph
Type: Technical
Severity: Critical
Description: The paper applies Welch's t-test throughout and justifies it via Shapiro-Wilk (non-normality) and Levene's test (unequal variances). However, Welch's t-test is a parametric test that assumes approximate normality, particularly for the sampling distribution of the mean. With n=30, the Central Limit Theorem provides some protection, but the paper simultaneously reports "non-normality (p < .05 for M-family distributions)" and applies Welch's t-test. For distributions that are substantially non-normal (e.g., the ARM Graviton H.265 data with std=71.85s and median=700.5s, suggesting heavily right-skewed distributions or multimodal behavior), parametric tests are inappropriate regardless of sample size. A non-parametric alternative (Mann-Whitney U test) should have been used, or at minimum, the authors should demonstrate that the non-normality is mild enough that Welch's t-test remains valid. The paper never shows the shape of these distributions. The massive standard deviations in Table 5 (ARM Graviton H.265: std=71.86s against median=700.5s, and std=30.58s against median=59.27s for horizontal) suggest multimodal or heavily skewed distributions. Applying Welch's t-test to these is methodologically unsound.
Suggested fix: Use the Mann-Whitney U test for all non-normal distributions. If Welch's t-test is retained, provide QQ-plots or histograms in supplementary material demonstrating that the distribution shapes are close enough to normal for the CLT to apply. At minimum, report both parametric and non-parametric test results for the ARM Graviton comparisons.

Issue 2.2
Location: Section III, Phase 3 statistical methods
Type: Technical
Severity: Critical
Description: The paper reports Cohen's d for Phase 3 comparisons: d=3.74 (T-family), d=8.77 (M-family), d=7.69 (C-family). Cohen's d assumes the two groups being compared have approximately normal distributions. The paper has just confirmed non-normality for Phase 3 execution times (Shapiro-Wilk p<.05). For non-normal data, Cohen's d is not a valid effect size measure. The appropriate non-parametric effect size would be rank-biserial correlation (for Mann-Whitney) or Cliff's delta. Furthermore, a Cohen's d of 8.77 is extraordinarily large — this value is so extreme that it suggests the comparison may be between distributions that don't overlap at all, in which case the effect size is trivially obvious and statistically uninformative. The authors should question whether reporting such extreme effect sizes adds scientific value.
Suggested fix: Replace Cohen's d with appropriate non-parametric effect size measures for non-normally distributed data. Report Cliff's delta or rank-biserial correlation. For the extreme d values, note that they merely confirm non-overlapping distributions and offer interpretive commentary rather than raw numbers.

Issue 2.3
Location: Section IV.B.i (Efficiency and Cost Calculation), Equation 1
Type: Technical
Severity: Major
Description: The Efficiency metric is defined as 1/((cost/3600)×time). The authors describe this as an "Inverse Cost-Delay Product, conceptually analogous to the Energy-Delay Product." However, the Energy-Delay Product (EDP) is typically defined as E×D (energy × delay), and its inverse (1/EDP) is used to maximize efficiency. The paper's metric is 1/(cost × time), which is indeed an inverse cost-delay product. However, the metric conflates two very different things: "cost" in the denominator is an instantaneous rate (dollars per hour), not the total cost of the operation. The total cost is already computed separately in Equation 2. The Efficiency metric, as defined, is equivalent to 1/(Total_Cost × time) × 3600, which means it doubly penalizes time (once in cost, which increases with time, and once in the time term). This means efficiency is proportional to 1/time², not 1/(cost×time). The authors should clarify whether this double-penalization of time is intentional and theoretically justified, because it means the metric is not actually an "inverse cost-delay product" but rather an "inverse cost-delay-squared" metric.
Verification: Efficiency = 1/((R/3600)×T) where R = hourly rate, T = time in seconds. Total Cost = (R/3600)×T. So Efficiency = 1/Total_Cost. This means Efficiency is simply the reciprocal of Total Cost. If that is all this metric is, then reporting both Efficiency and Total Cost in Table 2 is redundant — they carry identical information. The paper never acknowledges this.
Suggested fix: Either (a) recognize that Efficiency = 1/Total_Cost and remove the redundant column, or (b) redefine Efficiency as throughput per dollar: (1/T) / (R/3600) = 3600/(R×T), which is a legitimate performance-per-cost metric. In either case, revise the theoretical framing to match the actual computation.

Issue 2.4
Location: Section IV.D, ARM Graviton results, Table 5
Type: Technical
Severity: Major
Description: The paper reports that the m7g.large serial H.265 execution consumed 700.5 seconds (median) with std=71.86s. The minimum is 328.92s and maximum is 718.51s. This is a bimodal or highly skewed distribution — the minimum (328.92s) is dramatically lower than the median (700.5s). The authors attribute this to "software-hardware impedance mismatch" and "sequential software emulation." However, the existence of observations as low as 328.92s (nearly half the median) suggests that some executions ran on a fundamentally different code path or had access to different hardware features. The paper does not investigate or explain this bimodality. Furthermore, if some executions achieved 328.92s (plausibly using NEON SIMD), then the median of 700.5s may be the artifact, not the norm. The authors make strong claims about "severe slowdown" and "software emulation" without investigating the root cause of this variance.
Suggested fix: Plot the distribution of H.265 serial execution times on m7g.large. Investigate whether the 328.92s observations correlate with specific system configurations or AWS hypervisor assignments. Do not make causal claims about SIMD emulation without confirming this via profiling (e.g., perf stat, or checking compiler flags of the system libx265 binary).

Issue 2.5
Location: Section III, Phase 1 Methodology
Type: Technical
Severity: Major
Description: The paper deploys 100 instances per configuration to measure hardware heterogeneity. In zone 'a', 98/100 t3.micro instances used Xeon 8259CL and 2/100 used Xeon 8175M. The paper then pins all experiments to the dominant architecture. However, the methodology for ensuring hardware pinning is never described mechanistically. The paper states "instances underwent architectural validation, with any non-conforming instances immediately terminated and automatically replaced." This raises several unaddressed questions: (1) How many replacement cycles were needed on average? (2) Does the selective termination-and-replace loop introduce a systematic bias by preferentially sampling from a subset of the physical host pool? (3) Does repeatedly requesting the same instance type in the same AZ during replacement attempts affect the distribution of assigned hardware? Without answers to these questions, the "architectural validation" protocol is not reproducible and may introduce subtle confounds.
Suggested fix: Report the distribution of replacement attempts (mean, max replacements needed per experimental run). Justify that the replacement protocol does not introduce systematic bias in host selection. Consider using instance placement groups or dedicated hosts as a more principled approach to hardware homogeneity.

Issue 2.6
Location: Section IV.C.ii (Effective Encoding Time analysis)
Type: Technical
Severity: Major
Description: The paper states "effective encoding takes 1.72 minutes (103 seconds), implying a theoretical per-instance computational share of ≈0.17 minutes when distributed across 10 nodes. The reported parallel Effective Encoding Time of 0.22 minutes reflects both raw FFmpeg computation and inherent network I/O transfers." This analysis contains an error: 103 seconds / 10 nodes = 10.3 seconds = 0.172 minutes per node. But the paper states this is "≈0.17 minutes," which matches. The parallel Effective Encoding Time of 0.22 min = 13.2 seconds. The overhead over ideal (0.17 min) is 0.05 minutes = 3 seconds, attributed to SFTP transfer overhead. This seems plausible for a 1-minute video segment. However, the paper never validates that this overhead is truly SFTP transfer time — it could include FFmpeg startup time, container initialization, output container stop, etc. The attribution to "network I/O transfers" without measurement is a claim not supported by data.
Suggested fix: Instrument the parallel workflow to separately measure FFmpeg execution time vs. SFTP transfer time vs. container startup time within each worker node. Report these breakdowns in the artifact data.

Issue 2.7
Location: Phase 4, Equation 3 (T(c) model)
Type: Technical
Severity: Major
Description: The analytical model defines T(c) = t_seg + max(t_prov,i) + t_enc(c) + t_merge. This model is incomplete for several reasons: (1) It models provisioning as a single max() operation, but the actual pipeline is sequential: segment → provision → transfer → encode → retrieve → merge. The transfer time is missing from the model. (2) t_enc(c) is treated as a scalar, but in practice it is the maximum encoding time across all N nodes (which varies due to AWS jitter). The model should be T(c) = t_seg + max(t_prov,i) + max(t_transfer,i) + max(t_enc,i) + t_merge. (3) The model claims to "establish the mathematical bounds for optimal segment duration" but no closed-form optimal c is derived. The authors present the model and then immediately pivot to empirical results (Table 6) without showing where dT/dc = 0 or how the optimal is determined analytically. The claim of "analytical chunk optimization model" is not fulfilled — this is an empirical sensitivity analysis with a decorative equation.
Suggested fix: Either (a) derive the actual optimal c analytically (requires characterizing t_enc(c) as linear in c, t_prov as independent of c, etc.) or (b) rename Section IV.D as "Empirical Chunk Size Sensitivity Analysis" and remove the claim of "analytical" modeling. The model as presented does not meet the standard of an analytical contribution.

Issue 2.8
Location: Phase 2 Results, thread scaling analysis for VP9
Type: Technical
Severity: Major
Description: The paper states "The VP9 codec (libvpx-vp9) exhibits a distinct behavior, maintaining near-constant execution times across all thread configurations and instance types." From Table 2: VP9 times across instances range from 14.45s (c5.4xlarge) to 18.05s (t3.large). These are NOT "near-constant across instance types" — there is a 24.7% range. The "near-constant" claim applies specifically to thread configurations within a given instance, not across instances. This is a significant semantic error. Furthermore, the explanation — "without explicit structural parameters such as spatial tiling, the encoder cannot effectively exploit parallel vCPU resources" — is presented as an interpretation but is not empirically validated. The paper does not test VP9 with tile-columns or tile-rows parameters enabled, so it cannot claim that the lack of tiling is the cause.
Suggested fix: Correct the scope of the "near-constant" claim to apply only to thread counts within a single instance, not across instance types. Qualify the tiling explanation as a hypothesis rather than a confirmed finding. Consider running a single VP9 experiment with tile-columns=4 to empirically validate the tiling hypothesis.

SECTION 3: SEMANTIC AND LOGICAL CONSISTENCY

Issue 3.1
Location: Introduction, RQ3 and RQ4 vs. Results
Type: Semantic
Severity: Major
Description: RQ3 asks: "Can provisioning optimizations make small-instance clusters more effective than vertical scaling in both time and cost?" This is answered. RQ4 asks: "How do regional pricing disparities and network egress bottlenecks impact the ultimate economic viability of VaaS deployments?" The regional pricing section (IV.D) quantifies a 44% premium but does not conclude when cross-region deployment becomes economically irrational. The network egress section (IV.D Phase 4) shows egress costs exceed compute costs by ~6.4× for t3.micro clusters, but does not address "economic viability" of VaaS at scale. RQ4 is only partially answered — the "impact on economic viability" is never quantitatively characterized. At what egress volume does the service become unprofitable? What is the break-even between compute optimization and CDN offloading? These questions are implied by RQ4 but never addressed.
Suggested fix: Either narrow RQ4 to what is actually answered ("How do regional pricing disparities and network egress costs compare to compute costs?") or expand Section IV.D to compute break-even points and viability thresholds.

Issue 3.2
Location: Section IV.D, ARM Graviton H.264 horizontal performance
Type: Semantic
Severity: Major
Description: The paper states that for H.264 on m7g.large, "serial execution pattern produced faster absolute completion times (57.55s) than the parallel cluster architecture (108.07s), indicating severe architectural mismatch." The paper then attributes this inversion to "the computational translation is so rapid that the inherent variance in AWS EC2 provisioning latency… completely eclipses the parallel speedup." However, the total pipeline for horizontal includes segmentation, provisioning, transfer, encoding, retrieval, and merging. For H.264 on Graviton, each segment encodes in ~10 seconds (57.55s / ~6 segments for a 10-minute video with 60-second chunks ≈ 9.59s per segment). But the paper never shows the per-segment encoding time for Graviton H.264 to confirm that encoding is fast enough that overhead dominates. The causal attribution is asserted but not demonstrated with per-phase timing data.
Suggested fix: Provide per-phase timing breakdown (provision, transfer, encode, retrieve) for Graviton H.264 horizontal to demonstrate empirically that provisioning overhead dominates. This is necessary to support the causal claim.

Issue 3.3
Location: Section IV.D, ARM Graviton H.265 performance claim
Type: Semantic
Severity: Critical
Description: The paper claims the "horizontal m7g.large cluster processed the same workload in 59.27 seconds utilizing H.265, bypassing even the fastest x86 H.264 results." The fastest x86 H.264 horizontal result is c5.large at 64.04s (Table 4). The m7g.large H.265 horizontal achieves 59.27s. This comparison is not scientifically valid — it compares different codecs (H.264 vs H.265) on different architectures. H.265 at equivalent quality produces smaller files, so a fair comparison would need to control for output quality (PSNR/SSIM) or use the same codec on both platforms. The paper is comparing encoding speed of a more complex codec (H.265) on ARM against a simpler codec (H.264) on x86. This is analogous to claiming "my computer compresses files faster" by switching to a less compressive algorithm on one machine. This comparison is scientifically meaningless as stated.
Suggested fix: Remove or heavily qualify this cross-codec comparison. If comparing ARM vs x86 performance, use the same codec on both. The paper should compare H.265 on ARM vs H.265 on x86, not H.265-ARM vs H.264-x86.

Issue 3.4
Location: Conclusion, paragraph 3
Type: Semantic
Severity: Major
Description: The conclusion states "ARM Graviton instances displayed strong parallel encoding performance for H.265 workloads, surpassing x86 performance at a lower operational cost." This claim is not supported by the data for two reasons: (1) As noted in Issue 3.3, the comparison is cross-codec; (2) The m7g.large H.265 horizontal results show a median of 59.27s but with std=30.58s and maximum=225.79s. The paper earlier acknowledges this represents "operational volatility" with CV>50%. Claiming "strong performance" for a configuration with CV>50% is contradictory — high variance is antithetical to "strong" reliable performance. A result that sometimes takes 4× longer than the median is not a reliable performance advantage.
Suggested fix: Qualify: "ARM Graviton demonstrated median H.265 horizontal encoding advantages over x86, but exhibited substantial operational variance (CV>50%) that limits production reliability without further orchestration hardening."

Issue 3.5
Location: Section II (Related Works), last paragraph before Table 1
Type: Semantic
Severity: Minor
Description: The paper states "Our work addresses cloud performance variability through empirical measurement. We quantify variability across 30 trials per configuration." The justification of 30 trials is never argued — why is n=30 sufficient? For non-normal distributions (as later confirmed by Shapiro-Wilk tests), the CLT may require larger samples for the sample mean to be approximately normally distributed, particularly for the ARM Graviton configurations which show extreme variance. The choice of n=30 appears to be a convenience threshold (the traditional rule-of-thumb for the CLT) rather than a power-analysis-justified sample size.
Suggested fix: Include a brief power analysis justifying n=30 as sufficient given the observed effect sizes and variance levels. For configurations with CV>50% (ARM Graviton), explicitly discuss whether n=30 provides adequate statistical power.

Issue 3.6
Location: Section IV.B.iii (Visual Analysis) and Figure 1 caption
Type: Semantic
Severity: Major
Description: The caption for Figure 1 states "Compression time (mean ± 95% CI, n=30)." However, the methodology states "We computed descriptive statistics across these repetitions, calculating 95% Confidence Intervals (Student's t-distribution)." Student's t-distribution assumes normality, but Shapiro-Wilk tests confirmed non-normality for M-family distributions. The figure caption claims "mean ± 95% CI" but for non-normal distributions, the mean is not a robust central tendency measure — the median should be reported. Furthermore, Table 2 uses "Median" as the central tendency metric, making the figure caption inconsistent with the table. The paper reports median in the table but appears to plot mean in the figure.
Suggested fix: Either (a) use median with bootstrapped 95% CIs in the figure, consistent with Table 2, or (b) justify why mean is appropriate for the figure while median is used in the table. The inconsistency between the table's use of median and the figure's use of mean must be resolved.

Issue 3.7
Location: Section IV.B.ii, thread scaling discussion
Type: Semantic
Severity: Minor
Description: The paper explains VP9's thread-agnostic behavior as: "without explicit structural parameters such as spatial tiling, the encoder cannot effectively exploit parallel vCPU resources for the evaluated 30-second workload segments." This explanation is correct for libvpx-vp9, which historically had limited thread parallelism. However, the paper's FFmpeg command uses -threads <n> for VP9 without specifying -tile-columns and -tile-rows. The paper presents the absence of these parameters as an intentional experimental condition (to evaluate "default configurations") but never states this explicitly. A reader unfamiliar with VP9's parallelism model might incorrectly conclude that VP9 is simply not parallelizable, when in fact it is parallelizable with proper configuration. The experimental design decision to use default parameters for all codecs should be explicitly justified as representing the typical deployment scenario.
Suggested fix: Add a sentence explicitly stating that the experiment evaluates default libvpx-vp9 configuration as representative of naive deployments, and note that tiling parameters exist but are outside the scope of this study.

SECTION 4: SYNTACTIC AND GRAMMATICAL CORRECTNESS

Issue 4.1
Location: Introduction, paragraph 4, sentence: "Four primary research questions guide this investigation"
Type: Syntactic
Severity: Minor
Description: The four research questions are formatted as inline parenthetical enumeration (1)...(2)...(3)...(4)... within a single sentence spanning four complex clauses. This creates a run-on sentence that is difficult to parse in academic writing. IEEE conference papers conventionally separate research questions as distinct items or short paragraphs.
Suggested fix: Break into a bulleted or numbered list or separate sentences: "RQ1: How do cost-performance profiles differ... RQ2: What provisioning overheads..."

Issue 4.2
Location: Section IV.D, ARM Graviton section, sentence: "Intriguingly, for the H.264 codec on ARM, the serial execution pattern produced faster absolute completion times (57.55s) than the parallel cluster architecture (108.07s), indicating severe architectural mismatch and overhead when chunking H.264 segments."
Type: Syntactic/Semantic
Severity: Minor
Description: "Intriguingly" is an informal, editorializing adverb inappropriate for IEEE academic writing. Similarly, "Conversely, the most striking anomaly" in the following sentence uses "striking" which is a hyperbolic adjective. Academic writing should report findings without such value-laden language.
Suggested fix: Replace "Intriguingly" with "Unexpectedly" or simply restructure: "For H.264 on ARM, serial execution (57.55s) outperformed the parallel cluster (108.07s), an inversion attributable to..." Remove "most striking anomaly" → "a notable anomaly."

Issue 4.3
Location: Section IV.D, ARM Graviton section: "This confirms that migrating modern encoding pipelines to ARM necessitates custom-compiled, architecture-aware binaries to avoid severe serial performance degradation."
Type: Semantic/Syntactic
Severity: Major
Description: The word "confirms" implies this was a previously established fact being re-verified. This is actually a new finding of this paper. Furthermore, "necessitates" is too strong — the paper shows that standard Ubuntu repository binaries perform poorly, but has not tested custom-compiled binaries. You cannot confirm a mitigation you have not tested. This sentence presents an untested recommendation as an empirical confirmation.
Suggested fix: Replace with: "These results suggest that migrating encoding pipelines to ARM may require custom-compiled, architecture-aware binaries to achieve optimal performance, a hypothesis warranting direct empirical validation."

Issue 4.4
Location: Section IV.D, sentence: "...the cloud's unavoidable orchestration jitter—completely eclipses the parallel speedup."
Type: Syntactic
Severity: Minor
Description: "Jitter" in italics with preceding em-dash creates a long parenthetical interruption that breaks reading flow. The sentence structure is: "For libx264 on Graviton, the computational translation is so rapid that the inherent variance in AWS EC2 provisioning latency, OS boot times, and network chunk transfer—the cloud's unavoidable orchestration jitter—completely eclipses the parallel speedup." This is grammatically valid but the em-dash parenthetical interrupts the subject-verb-object flow too severely for a technical paper.
Suggested fix: Restructure: "For libx264 on Graviton, the encoding is sufficiently fast that AWS EC2 provisioning latency, OS boot times, and network chunk transfer overhead (collectively, cloud orchestration jitter) completely eclipses the parallel speedup."

Issue 4.5
Location: Section IV.D, Regional Cost Disparities: "Therefore, transferring workloads to cheaper regions may be invalidated solely by either unpredictable orchestrational jitter or cross-region data egress costs."
Type: Syntactic
Severity: Minor
Description: "orchestrational" is not a standard English word. The correct term is "orchestration." Also, "invalidated solely by either X or Y" means that X alone is sufficient to invalidate, Y alone is sufficient to invalidate, but they cannot both simultaneously invalidate — which is an odd claim. The intended meaning is likely "may be negated by orchestration jitter or egress costs."
Suggested fix: "transferring workloads to cheaper regions may be economically counterproductive due to orchestration jitter or cross-region data egress costs."

Issue 4.6
Location: Section IV.E (limitations), External Validity: "...relying on standard Linux repository binaries often strangles ARM-native capabilities."
Type: Syntactic
Severity: Minor
Description: "strangles" is an informal, colloquial verb inappropriate for an IEEE A1 paper. This is the kind of language that would appear in a blog post, not a peer-reviewed publication.
Suggested fix: "...relying on standard Linux repository binaries may severely limit ARM-native computational capabilities."

Issue 4.7
Location: Phase 3.2 results discussion: "These results alter the cost dynamics of cloud media scaling."
Type: Syntactic
Severity: Minor
Description: "alter" is too weak and vague. The results do not merely "alter" cost dynamics — they quantify specific improvements. This sentence is also an unsupported broad claim.
Suggested fix: "These results quantify the cost-performance implications of horizontal vs. vertical scaling strategies across all three instance families."

Issue 4.8
Location: Section IV.D, ARM Graviton: "This confirms that non-deterministic cloud orchestration constraints dictate horizontal scaling viability as rigidly as CPU architecture."
Type: Syntactic/Semantic
Severity: Major
Description: "as rigidly as CPU architecture" is an unsubstantiated qualitative comparison. The paper has not quantified how rigidly CPU architecture dictates scaling viability, so the comparison is meaningless. Furthermore, "dictate... viability" uses a dramatic causal verb that overstates the finding.
Suggested fix: "This result demonstrates that provisioning latency can exceed codec-specific encoding performance differences as a determinant of horizontal scaling effectiveness."

Issue 4.9
Location: Abstract: "a non-negligible instance provisioning overhead, consuming up to 93.3% of total execution time"
Type: Syntactic
Severity: Minor
Description: "non-negligible" is an understatement for a 93.3% overhead. This is the dominant component of execution time, not merely "non-negligible." The abstract should accurately characterize the magnitude.
Suggested fix: "a dominant instance provisioning overhead, consuming up to 93.3% of total execution time"

SECTION 5: STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY

Issue 5.1
Location: Section III (Methodology) vs. Section IV (Results)
Type: Structural
Severity: Major
Description: The methodology describes "Phase 4: Analytical Modeling" as comprising two sub-models: (1) Chunk Optimization Model and (2) Network Cost Model. The results section (IV.E) is titled "Phase 4 Results: Analytical Modeling and Validation" and covers both. However, the methodology section describes Phase 4 as primarily "formalizing empirical findings," but there is no Phase 4 "methods" content explaining how the analytical models were derived, what assumptions underlie them, or how they were validated against empirical data. The methodology for Phase 4 is described in one short paragraph, but it is insufficient for a contribution the abstract claims as a primary result. Specifically: the Network Cost Model derivation (Equation 4) appears entirely in the Results section without a methodological preamble, and the parameters (R_inst, T_i, R_egress, D_out) are defined inline in the Results section rather than in the Methodology section. This violates the structural principle that methodology precedes results.
Suggested fix: Expand the Phase 4 methodology to include the parameter definitions, assumptions (e.g., linear billing, independence of compute and egress costs), and validation approach for both models. Move Equation 4's parameter definitions to Section III.

Issue 5.2
Location: Section IV, missing Phase for ARM/Regional analysis
Type: Structural
Severity: Major
Description: Section IV.D is titled "Architecture, Codec, and Regional Impact Analysis" and contains what the paper calls "extended evaluations (M1, M2, M3)" in the LaTeX comments. However, the methodology section (Section III) describes only Phases 1–4. The ARM Graviton tests and regional replications are described in Phase 3 methodology but split out as a separate section in the results. The LaTeX comment markers % EXTENDED EVALUATIONS (M1, M2, M3) suggest these were originally separate subsections that were merged without updating the methodology structure. The mismatch creates a structural disconnect: readers expecting Phase 3 Results to cover the ARM and regional analyses find them in a separate section without a corresponding methodology subsection.
Suggested fix: Either integrate the ARM and regional analyses into Section IV.C (Phase 3 Results) as subsections, or add a "Phase 3 Extended Evaluation" subsection in the methodology that explicitly scopes the ARM Graviton and regional experiments.

Issue 5.3
Location: All figure and table references
Type: Structural
Severity: Critical
Description: The paper references Figure 1 (fig:unified_codecs) in Section IV.B.iv. The figure appears after the text referencing it (placement with [!ht]). This is acceptable in IEEE format. Figure 2 (fig:unified_scaling) is referenced in Section IV.C.ii and placed with [!ht]. However, Table 6 (tab:chunk_sensitivity) appears in Section IV.E (Phase 4) and is referenced in the same section, which is fine. Critical issue: Table 5 (tab:arm_graviton_scaling) is referenced in the text of Section IV.D but the reference is inline with the discussion. However, the label tab:arm_graviton_scaling is referenced as "Table~\ref{tab:arm_graviton_scaling}" in Section IV.D, and the table is placed with [h] specifier. More importantly: Table 4 (tab:regional_cost) is referenced in the text of Section IV.D ("Table~\ref{tab:regional_cost} details this explicit empirical divergence") but is placed with [h] specifier in the same section. This is structurally sound. However, I find no in-text reference to Table 1 (tab:comparative_analysis) — searching the text, this table is described in the related works section but never explicitly cited as "Table~\ref{tab:comparative_analysis}" with a \ref command. The table is discussed but not formally referenced. In IEEE papers, all tables must be referenced in the text.
