SECTION 6: BIBLIOGRAPHIC COMPLETENESS

Issue 6.1
Location: Bibliography, \bibitem{awscredits}
Type: Bibliographic
Severity: Major
Description: The citation \cite{awscredits} refers to an AWS documentation page cited as: "Amazon Web Services, 'Burstable performance instances,' Amazon EC2 User Guide, 2024." This is a web document with no DOI, no volume, no page numbers, and no archival stability guarantee. AWS documentation URLs change and content is updated without version tracking. For IEEE publications, web citations should include a [Accessed: date] field. More importantly, this citation is used to support the critical claim about T-family CPU credit mechanics — a claim central to the paper's cost analysis. Relying on a live web page for a central empirical claim is a reproducibility risk.
Suggested fix: Add "[Accessed: Month Year]" to the citation. Consider supplementing with the AWS whitepaper on EC2 burstable instances (which is a more stable document) or citing the academic literature on burstable instance behavior.

Issue 6.2
Location: Bibliography completeness check
Type: Bibliographic
Severity: Major
Description: The paper evaluates ARM Graviton 3 instances extensively but cites no primary literature on ARM Graviton architecture or performance. AWS has published technical documentation and benchmark reports on Graviton 3 (e.g., AWS Graviton3 processor technical whitepapers). The paper's claim that Graviton 3 offers "100% baseline homogeneity" and its attribution of H.265 slowdown to "sequential software emulation" without NEON SIMD would benefit from citing AWS Graviton3 architectural documentation or academic papers on ARM server performance. Additionally, the paper discusses SIMD optimizations for video codecs on ARM but cites no work on ARM NEON in video encoding (e.g., work on HEVC/H.265 SIMD optimization on ARM). This represents a significant gap in the related work.
Suggested fix: Add citations for: (1) AWS Graviton3 technical documentation; (2) academic work on ARM NEON optimizations for video codecs; (3) at least one paper studying Graviton vs x86 performance in cloud workloads.

Issue 6.3
Location: Section II, discussion of energy efficiency (b8)
Type: Bibliographic
Severity: Minor
Description: Reference b8 (Katsenou et al.) is described as focusing on "embedded devices" in Table 1, but the actual citation is to a 2024 Picture Coding Symposium paper on "Comparative Study of Hardware and Software Power Measurements in Video Compression." The paper's characterization of b8 as "embedded devices focus" in the gap analysis is potentially inaccurate and should be verified. If the Katsenou paper addresses cloud or server platforms as well as embedded devices, characterizing it solely as "embedded devices" misrepresents the prior work.
